# package-lock.json tends to drift on branch switches between darwin and
# linux because npm regenerates the rollup `libc` field differently on
# each platform. This is purely noise — the actual package versions are
# identical. The `merge=ours` strategy tells git to keep whichever copy
# of the file is already on the current branch during a merge, and the
# combination with the `binary` attribute avoids a line-by-line diff.
#
# To make this work, the operator also needs to declare the "ours"
# merge driver once per clone:
#
#     git config merge.ours.driver true
#
# That's a one-time setup step documented in the chore/gitattributes
# commit that introduced this file. Without it, the attribute is a no-op
# and git falls back to the default merge strategy.
package-lock.json merge=ours
